        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/pitrinetro/{size}/43890_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-03-24T21:38:31.706Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"CueHD\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"67686\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/cuehd/48/42510_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> CueHD:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Using one of the suggestions above would also let you use the official Signal-Desktop client as a linked device.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>It is the official client that I use though. Ever since right after I registered my account.</p>\n<p>The only time you need to enable and custom compile is for the registration process itself; otherwise, the code to use Signal as standalone remains unused in the Signal distributed app, though it’s always been there, including when Desktop was merely a Chrome browser extension.</p>\n<p>The reason I go with this setup instead of Signal-CLI is that it doesn’t involve maintaining, updating, and tracking user files for software that I have no use for on regular basis, past the registration.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"CueHD\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"67686\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/cuehd/48/42510_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> CueHD:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>an Android emulator</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I’m not sure which specific ones you use (I assume you do since you made that suggestion), but the last time I checked, Android emulators were absolutely dreadful.</p>",
